    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just in case someone is lost. For both new application or existing ones go to File->Project Structure. Then in Project settings on the left pane select Project for the Java SDK and select Modules for Android SDK.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14358,
      "reputation" : 1138,
      "user_id" : 29472,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cb9a878b38f6fb132c595346552ac554?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Alan Samet",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/29472/alan-samet"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1378862802,
    "creation_date" : 1378862802,
    "answer_id" : 18731299,
    "question_id" : 5271182,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had some issues that this didn't address in getting this environment set up on OSX. It had to do with the solution that I was maintaining having additional dependencies on some of the Google APIs. It wasn't enough to just download and install the items listed in the first response.</p>\n\n<p>You have to download these. </p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Run <strong>Terminal</strong></li>\n<li>Navigate to the android/sdk directory</li>\n<li>Type \"android\" You will get a gui. Check the \"Tools\" directory and the latest Android API (at this time, it's 4.3 (API 18)).</li>\n<li>Click \"Install xx packages\" and go watch an episode of Breaking Bad or something. It'll take a while. </li>\n<li>Go back to IntelliJ and open the \"Project Structure...\" dialog (Cmd+;). </li>\n<li>In the left panel of the dialog, under \"Project Settings,\" select Project. In the right panel, under \"Project SDK,\" click \"New...\" > Android SDK and navigate to your android/sdk directory. Choose this and you will be presented with a dialog with which you can add the \"Google APIs\" build target. This is what I needed. You may need to do this more than once if you have multiple version targets. </li>\n<li>Now, under the left pane \"Modules,\" with your project selected in the center pane, select the appropriate module under the \"Dependencies\" tab in the right pane. </li>\n</ol>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2888687,
      "reputation" : 29,
      "user_id" : 2477955,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/936f95d0e8650ac59893f5ed2ed512ac?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Sheesh Kabob",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2477955/sheesh-kabob"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1399904467,
    "creation_date" : 1399904467,
    "answer_id" : 23611560,
    "question_id" : 5271182,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You just need to install Android development kit from <a href=\"http://developer.android.com/sdk/installing/studio.html#Updating\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://developer.android.com/sdk/installing/studio.html#Updating</a></p>\n\n<p>and also Download and install Java JDK (Choose the Java platform)</p>\n\n<p>define the environment variable in windows System setting <a href=\"https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Setting+the+JAVA_HOME+Variable+in+Windows\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Setting+the+JAVA_HOME+Variable+in+Windows</a></p>\n\n<p>Voila ! You are Donezo !</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10023879,
      "reputation" : 41,
      "user_id" : 7412637,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/29b1a9fd3233ec1ab0bd1528c7d5d3e8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "KellieT",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7412637/kelliet"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1484300258,
    "last_edit_date" : 1484300258,
    "creation_date" : 1484271528,
    "answer_id" : 41626097,
    "question_id" : 5271182,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Another way to identify the correct SDK is to install Android Studio, create a new project, go to project structure, SDK Location and find where the SDK was installed.</p>\n\n<p>I found using the default installation process on a mac that the SDK home folder was in the <code>/Users/'yourUser'/Library/Android/sdk</code> folder.  Make sure you have enabled your Mac to view the <em>Library</em> folder.</p>\n"
  } ],
